<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Palestinian-Israeli Committees Continue Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Palestinian-Israeli Committees Continue Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Sha'th, PLO Commander on `Difficulties' </H4>

<F P=102> NC0604142894 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1345 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0604142894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 6 Apr (MENA)--Chief Palestinian negotiator 
Nabil Sha'th has said that the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations 
are facing difficulties "but we are seeking a solution to them." 
  In a statement today, Sha'th said the Palestinian forces are 
not ready to enter Gaza and Jericho. He said they will first 
come to Egypt from several Arab countries. 
  The Palestinian official called on the donor states to meet 
their obligations now, not after the signing of the agreement. 
He said the Palestinians need cash to finance arrangements for 
the entry of the Palestinian police into Gaza and Jericho. 
  Sha'th said Norway is the only country to pay for the 
Palestinian police. It has paid $2 million. The other donor 
countries have not met their obligations, he said. 
  Sha'th said the water issue will be discussed at the 
Civilian 
Affairs Committee in the next round of negotiations. 
  Nasr Yusuf, a PLO military commander, has stated that the 
vanguards of the Palestinian police force, who were scheduled to 
enter Gaza and Jericho, will not now go there due to problems 
facing the negotiations. 
  He said there has been no agreement on the final size of the 
police force or the timetable for its entry into the self-rule 
areas. 
  Yusuf said the Israelis are linking agreement on the start 
of 
the negotiations with the signing of an agreement on the 
implementation of the Palestinian-Israeli Declaration of 
Principles [sentence as received]. 
  The Palestinian official denied that the two sides agreed 
that the Palestinian police force should consist of 9,000 men. 
  In a related development, MENA has learned that difficulties 
appearing at the last minute prevented Israeli officers from 
handing over Israeli police barracks to PLO representatives in 
Gaza. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

