<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-067 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Palestinian-Israeli Committees Continue Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Palestinian-Israeli Committees Continue Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Sha'th: Israelis Obstructing Talks </H4>

<F P=102> NC0604173194 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1620 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0604173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 6 Apr (MENA)--Dr. Nabil Sha'th, political 
adviser to Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat and head of the 
Palestinian delegation to the negotiations with the Israelis on 
the implementation of the Gaza-Jericho agreement, has said that 
President 'Arafat reviewed the negotiations during his meeting 
with President Husni Mubarak this afternoon. 
  He said the Palestinians welcome any help to resolve the 
pending issues so that the Palestinian-Israeli Declaration of 
Principles can be implemented on schedule on 12 April. 
  Sha'th told journalists following the latest round of 
Palestinian-Israeli negotiations that President 'Arafat also 
discussed the results of the negotiations during his meeting 
with Spanish Foreign Minister Javier Solana. Egyptian Foreign 
Minister 'Amr Musa was also briefed on the results, he added. 
  Sha'th said: We did not achieve the progress we expected to 
achieve to sign the final agreement on schedule on 12 April. 
  He accused the Israeli delegation of obstructing the 
negotiations. Noting that the Israeli delegation left the 
negotiations at this time for a long recess (three and a half 
days) without finalizing the issues under discussion, Sha'th 
said: It is difficult to blame us for this; the Israelis are 
entirely to blame. 
  Sha'th said the Israeli delegation promised to continue the 
negotiations by fax and telephone. We are waiting to see if 
this will solve the remaining problems, he said. 
  He stressed that this depends largely on the intentions of 
the Israelis and their readiness to end the negotiations on 
time. If this is the case, he said, a practical result can be 
reached on Sunday or Monday. 
  Sha'th went on to say: We are working and are ready to work 
every minute of the remaining five and a half days before 
Tuesday 12 April. I firmly believe that if the Israelis have 
good intentions there is enough time to reaching an agreement. 
  The Palestinian official explained that the economic talks 
in 
Paris will continue tomorrow and the day after. Had these 
negotiations [in Cairo] been given a similar chance, he said, 
they would have been completed on time. 
  Sha'th said the Israeli delegation's ending the negotiations 
ahead of schedule on the pretext of marking the holocaust (the 
burning of Jews by the Nazis during World War II) means the 
Israelis have obstructed the negotiations in some way. 
  We could celebrate the intifadah or any other dear national 
Palestinian occasion by observing a silence or by breaking up 
the negotiations for an hour, he said. Ending the negotiations 
before their time in this way, he added, is an obstruction. 
  Sha'th stressed that the Palestinians still insist on the 
specified date for the implementation of the Gaza-Jericho 
agreement, that is, 13 April. He said this date is extremely 
important and must not be overlooked. There is enough time to 
achieve this, he said. 
  Sha'th added: The Israelis know full well what we want and 
what is required. I do not believe it is impossible to achieve 
what is required. 
  He said he tried to persuade the Israeli delegation to stay 
to complete the negotiations but the delegation insisted on 
leaving. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-12242 </DOCNO>
