<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Arafat Continues Visit, Meets With Officials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Arafat Continues Visit, Meets With Officials </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Musa, 'Arafat Comment on Talks </H4>

<F P=102> NC0604194694 Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network in 
Arabic 1830 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0604194694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa met Palestinian president 
Yasir 'Arafat this evening. Members of the delegation 
accompanying the Palestinian president attended. They discussed 
developments in the Palestinian issue and continued discussing 
topics that the Palestinian president reviewed today with 
President Mubarak. 
  Musa said afterward that he held contacts with Israeli 
Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres today on the Palestinian-Israeli 
peace talks and added that he hopes the talks will continue. He 
expressed his hope that the car bomb in Israel today will not 
affect the negotiations, because the peace process is important 
and fundamental. He said the peace process can put an end to 
violence and that the launch of a Palestinian entity, 
implementation of the Gaza-Jericho Accord, and a move toward 
implementing the timetable will all pacify the situation. He 
noted that what is required is a fast and sincere implementation 
of the provisions of the Declaration of Principles. 
  Palestinian president Yasir 'Arafat said his talks with 
President Husni Mubarak and Musa today were important, positive, 
and constructive and would contribute greatly to advancing the 
peace process. He added that regrettably, the Palestinian side 
has seen no real gestures from the Israeli side for a precise, 
sincere, and swift implementation of what was agreed upon 
recently. 
  [In two related Cairo-datelined reports, at 1835 GMT and 
1845 
GMT respectively on 6 April, Cairo MENA in Arabic adds the 
following: "Musa ruled out the possibility of visiting Israel 
right now." 
  ["'Arafat refused to answer a question on the explosion in 
Israel today."] 

</TEXT>

