<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Hijacking of Sudanese Plane to Luxor </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Hijacking of Sudanese Plane to Luxor </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Two Sudanese Ministers on Plane </H4>

<F P=102> NC0704101394 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0920 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0704101394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Khartoum, 7 Apr (MENA)--Sudanese newspapers today 
published conflicting reports on the Sudanese airliner that a 
Sudanese national hijacked yesterday, Wednesday, and forced to 
land at Luxor airport. 
  While AL-SUDAN AL-HADITH said the plane was bound for 
al-Danaqilah and then Jeddah, Saudi Arabia, AL-INQADH AL-WATANI 
said the plane was on a domestic flight. 
  AL-INQADH revealed that the hijacker Mahjub Husayn Muhammad, 
who requested asylum in Egypt, was registered on the flight as a 
passenger under a false name. He revealed his real name to the 
Egyptian authorities, the paper said, adding that the person who 
carried out the operation is called 'Adil Mahjub Muhammad Ahmad. 
  The paper explained that domestic flights are not subject to 
the same passenger-list checks that international flights 
usually undergo. 
  Meanwhile, all Sudanese media as well as statements made by 
the Sudanese information and media minister and Sudan airways 
totally disregarded the presence of Sudanese ministers on the 
plane that returned to Khartoum last night; the hijacked plane 
was carrying two ministers: Education Minister Ahmad Muhammad 
Kapuche and Agriculture Minister Yusuf Adam [names and titles as 
received]. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

