Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Algeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   FIS Conditions for Settlement of Crisis Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    FIS Conditions for Settlement of Crisis Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0504172794 Rabat Moroccan Kingdom Radio Network in Arabic 
1600 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0504172794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rabat Moroccan Kingdom Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Imprisoned leaders of the outlawed Islamic Salvation 
Front [FIS] have said that they have never previously committed 
themselves to issuing a appeal for halting violence in Algeria. 
A statement, signed by two FIS officials who were released by 
the Algerian authorities on 23 March, says that the imprisoned 
FIS leaders, chief among whom are Abassi Madani and Ali Belhadj, 
believe that a proposal made by General Liamine Zeroual when he 
was defense minister was premature and ineffective. 
  The FIS leaders' proposal calls for the drafting of an 
appeal 
urging the Algerian people to remain calm and confident. The 
two FIS officials cite three conditions laid down by the FIS 
leaders for a political settlement of the Algerian crisis. 
These conditions may be summed up as the total release of the 
front's leaders, the provision of comprehensive and detailed 
information on the general situation in the country, and the 
opening of a direct and comprehensive dialogue with various 
parties to decide the country's destiny. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-12256 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes067_a_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-067 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Algeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Leaders Said Working With Islamists </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Leaders Said Working With Islamists </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0604095694 Cairo AL-SHA'B in Arabic 1 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> NC0604095694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo AL-SHA'B </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Mahmud Bakri] </F>
  [Excerpt] AL-SHA'B has learned that approximately 160 
senior military commanders in the Algerian Army are secretly 
working with the Islamists. According to diplomatic reports, 
these commanders are planning to deal a crushing blow to the 
pillars of the regime in Algeria. Approximately 40 percent of 
the Algerian Army's equipment and weapons has reached the hands 
of Islamists between November of last year and this February. 
  A recent report by the U.S. State Department affirms that 
the 
Islamists' control of the Algerian regime would shatter 
stability in the Mediterranean, Red Sea, and Arab Gulf regions. 
The report expresses extreme concern at the prospects of the 
Islamists' reaching power in Algeria, particularly because the 
Algerian Army has proved to be extremely weak and divided before 
them. The report stresses that the Algerian Army will fall 
under the control of the Islamists in the next six months. The 
report does not rule out the possibility that the Islamists 
could rule Algeria by next year. 
  The report stresses the need for rapid intervention to 
rescue 
Algeria from the "fundamentalists" and giving the U.S. fleet in 
the Mediterranean specific prerogatives to monitor the situation 
and intervene immediately should conditions become unfavorable 
to the government. Accordingly, reports indicate that the U.S. 
Defense Department (the Pentagon) has been instructed to prepare 
a plan on the various political and military possibilities in 
Algeria in the coming stage and the U.S. role to deal with them. 
The U.S. report stresses that the Islamists' control of the 
country will be harmful to U.S. security in the Mediterranean, 
Red Sea, and the Arab Gulf. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

