<H3> <TI>   Executed Money Changer Reportedly Related to Saddam </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Executed Money Changer Reportedly Related to Saddam </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0604164994 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 3 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> JN0604164994 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] London -- 'Abbas 'Abd 'Awn, an important money 
changer, who was executed in Baghdad last Sunday, was reportedly 
related to President Saddam Husayn. Iraqi opposition sources 
told AL-HAYAH in London yesterday 'Awn "worked for an operation 
run by Saddam's sons 'Udayy and Qusayy, which traded in hard 
currency in Baghdad and elsewhere in Iraq, including the 
Kurdish-controlled north." 
  The Associated Press reported that Arab sources yesterday 
cited Iraqi officials as saying that 'Abbas 'Awn was convicted 
of dealing with "hostile external powers" bent on undermining 
the Iraqi dinar. 
  Travelers confirm the news of the execution. 'Awn had been 
apprehended on 3 January, 1994, but was then released. 
  According to the same sources, 'Abbas 'Awn was executed by 
firing squad, along with his brother-in-law, Qasim Qaqiyah, and 
others. 
  Sources of the "United National Iraqi Opposition" told 
AL-HAYAH the day before yesterday that 'Awn was bankrolling 
Iraq's military industries. Also executed with him were Majid 
Hulw, Qasim 'Abd-al-Karim Hasan, and his chaufeur. 

</TEXT>

