<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   YSP Statement on Military Buildup by North Denied </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    YSP Statement on Military Buildup by North Denied </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0604210394 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1620 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0604210394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sanaa, 6 Apr (MENA)--An official Yemeni source has 
denied a statement by an official at the Yemeni Socialist Party 
[YSP], led by 'Ali Salim al-Bid, about a north Yemeni military 
buildup on the former border regions between the north and the 
south of Yemen. The source said the YSP official's statement is 
not true and aims to cover up the military buildup and movements 
by the forces of the YSP in al-Dali' and Shabwah in the south. 
  The source warned against attempts by the YSP separatists, 
as 
he described them, to seriously escalate the military situation, 
dragging the country into a crushing civil war that could lead 
to separation and return the country to the situation it was in 
before 22 May 1990, the day unity was declared. 
  The Yemeni source said the YSP separatists are seeking 
military escalation to circumvent the Pledge and Accord document 
and hinder the implementation of the decisions made by the 
Council of Ministers in its latest meeting in Aden. The 
decisions provide for withdrawing troops from the former border 
regions. 
  The source denied reports that several countries offered 
proposals to solve the Yemeni crisis on the basis of federation 
or confederation. No Arab brother made such proposals. Indeed, 
they all stressed support for the Yemeni unity and its 
continuation, the source said. 
  The official Yemeni source stressed that the General 
People's 
Congress, led by President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih, is eager for 
dialogue among the political forces as the only option and the 
best solution to protect unity, reach understanding on common 
denominators to build the Yemeni state, and entrench the course 
of unity. 
  The source denied reports that during the meeting in Salalah 
in Oman, President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih threatened to resort to 
war to solve the crisis. The source said these reports are 
false and are being promoted to cover up the YSP's unjustified 
military escalation and preparation for war. 

</TEXT>

