<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-067 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Asad `Turned Down' Invitation To Visit Tehran </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Asad `Turned Down' Invitation To Visit Tehran </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0604160094 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 6 Apr 94 p4 </F>
<F P=103> PM0604160094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, London, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- Syrian 
President Hafiz al-Asad has turned down an Iranian invitation to 
visit Tehran later this month to discuss the Middle East peace 
process. 
  Sources in Tehran said yesterday that the invitation came in 
a written message from "Supreme Leader" 'Ali Khamene'i delivered 
to al-Asad in Damascus by Iranian Majles Deputy Speaker Hasan 
Ruhani. 
  Iranian media had reported that President al-Asad would 
visit 
Tehran this April to discuss "a new strategy for the Middle 
East" with Khamene'i and his aides. But sources in Tehran said 
yesterday that al-Asad accepted the invitation without setting a 
date for it. Ruhani, who is also secretary general of the 
Iranian National Security Council, also delivered a message from 
President 'Ali Akbar Hashemi-Rafsanjani. Khamene'i had openly 
urged Syria to withdraw from the "American peace process" and 
support the Palestinian factions which pledged to torpedo any 
agreement with Israel. 
  While in Damascus, Ruhani received a number of Palestinian 
radical leaders including Ahmad Jibril, Fathi Shaqaqi, and 
Colonel Abu-Musa [Sa'id Musa]. He invited George Habash and 
Nayif Hawatimah to meet with him but they sent representatives. 
  Ruhani, who is considered to be a member of the small circle 
of mullahs at the center of power in Tehran, also met with 
leaders of Lebanon's Hizballah. 
  The Iranian sources say that he asked the Hizballah leaders 
to persuade the Shiite leaders in Lebanon to accept Khamene'i as 
the highest Shiite authority. Senior Shiite leaders in Lebanon, 
including Muhammad Husayn Fadlallah and Muhammad Mahdi 
Shams-al-Din had expressed support for 'Ali Mohammad Sistani, 
the Iranian mullah living in al-Najaf in Iraq. 
  Some reports indicate that the Palestinian radical groups 
have expressed displeasure with Iran for failing so far to 
provide the massive aid it had promised at a special conference 
held in Tehran in February 1993. 
  Iranian sources attribute the delay in providing aid for 
these groups to Tehran's cash flow problems, but in a recent 
speech Khamene'i reaffirmed his government's commitment "to aid 
the Palestinian struggle" against the PLO-Israel agreement. 
  Tehran analysts believe that the summit meeting between 
Presidents al-Asad and Bill Clinton in Geneva last January was a 
turning point of historic importance in relations between 
Washington and Damascus. One of the results of that meeting is 
perhaps Damascus's clear attempts to gradually distance itself 
from Tehran's radical policies, according to the analysts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-12295 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes067_o_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-067 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Iranian Delegation Reaffirms Support for Factions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Iranian Delegation Reaffirms Support for Factions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0604152894 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 5 Apr 94 p2 </F>
<F P=103> PM0604152894 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Reports by Salwa al-Ustuwani and "news agencies": "Tehran </F>
Reaffirms Support for Palestinian Opposition Factions"] 
  [Text] Damascus -- An Iranian Majles delegation headed by 
Deputy Speaker Hasan Ruhani has started talks in Damascus with 
Syrian People's Assembly and other senior Syrian officials. 
  In Damascus yesterday, a highly placed Iranian official 
reaffirmed Tehran's support for the 10 Palestinian factions 
opposed to the PLO-Israel Gaza-Jericho autonomy agreement. 
  A Palestinian spokesman said that Iranian Deputy Majles 
Speaker Hasan Ruhani emphasized that position when he met with 
the leaders of the 10 factions at the Iranian Embassy in 
Damascus yesterday. 
  The spokesman said that the talks covered the situation in 
the region after the al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre and that the 
Iranian official reaffirmed his country's support for the 
Palestinian intifadah against the Israeli forces in the West 
Bank and the Gaza Strip. He added that the discussions also 
covered means and ways of providing aid for the intifadah and 
the 10 factions. 
  Ruhani, who leads a high-ranking delegation, told reporters 
on his arrival in Damascus the day before yesterday that he was 
carrying two messages for Syrian President Hafiz al-Asad from 
'Ali Khamene'i and President Hashemi-Rafsanjani on the issues of 
peace, the Gulf region, and bilateral relations between the two 
countries. 
  Some observers in Damascus believe that the two messages 
also 
deal with President al-Asad's forthcoming visit to Tehran 
scheduled to take place in the second half of this month. 

</TEXT>

