<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bhutto on Nuclear Program, U.S. Ties, Kashmir </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bhutto on Nuclear Program, U.S. Ties, Kashmir </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0704083094 Islamabad Radio Pakistan Overseas Service in 
English 0800 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0704083094 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad Radio Pakistan Overseas Service </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The prime minister, Ms. Benazir Bhutto, has 
categorically stated that Pakistan will not roll back its 
nuclear program. Addressing a news conference in the Parliament 
House in Islamabad this morning, she said this is a firm 
commitment of her government with the people of Pakistan. She 
said Pakistan will not open its nuclear facilities for 
inspection unilaterally as this would be discriminatory and 
against the wishes of the Pakistani nation. Ms. Benazir Bhutto 
emphasized that there should be an even-handed approach by the 
United States on the problem of nuclear nonproliferation, arms 
race, and missiles race, but these are to be resolved in South 
Asian subcontinent. Pakistan has given several positive 
proposals for nuclear nonproliferation in South Asia, but these 
have been rejected by India. 
  The prime minister said Pakistan wanted to improve bilateral 
relations with the United States not for acquisition of F-16 
aircraft or for arms purchases, but because Pakistan and the 
United States have a history of old friendship. She said the 
United States is now the only superpower and so it has a role to 
play in the solution of the Kashmir problem. Referring to the 
U.S. deputy secretary of state's forthcoming visit to Pakistan, 
Ms. Benazir Bhutto said Pakistan will inform Mr. Strobe Talbott 
that it believes in nonproliferation in South Asia, but there 
should a regional approach to it. 
  She also urged the opposition to give up its negative 
attitude of confrontation and join hands with the government on 
the sensitive issues of national importance like nuclear and 
Kashmir. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

