<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   ESCAP Session Continues in New Delhi </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ESCAP Session Continues in New Delhi </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Technology Transfer Discussed </H4>

<F P=102> BK0704085094 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0245 
GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0704085094 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Delhi ESCAP [Economic and Social Commission for 
Asia and the Pacific] session has finalized an action program 
for regional cooperation in technology transfer. It has been 
endorsed by the committee for regional economic cooperation 
which met yesterday under the chairmanship of the commerce 
secretary, Mr. Tejinder Khanna. The action program seeks to 
promote indigenous technological capabilities in the member 
countries. The private sector is sought to be involved in the 
implementation. Special attention will be given to the 
least-developed landlocked and island countries. 
  India has called for greater regional cooperation in the 
application of space technology, particularly for monitoring the 
management of environment. The environment secretary, Mr. P. 
Rajamani, told the ESCAP meeting that the Indian space program 
is tailored to meet the development needs of the country. He 
welcomed the move for a ministerial-level conference and offered 
New Delhi's full cooperation. 
  Today's discussions will (?cover), among other things, 
poverty alleviation through economic growth and social 
development. 

</TEXT>

