<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   YSP Said To Propose Egyptian Force To Disengage Troops </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    YSP Said To Propose Egyptian Force To Disengage Troops </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0604160694 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 2 Apr 94 pp 1, 4 </F>
<F P=103> JN0604160694 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By 'Abd-al-Rahman al-Haydari and Faysal Makram from Sanaa, </F>
and Iqbal 'Ali 'Abdallah from Aden] 
  [Excerpt] Yesterday, the Yemeni crisis witnessed a series 
of developments indicating an escalation. Reliable sources in 
Sanaa have reported that Presidential Council Chairman 
Lieutenant General 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih informed the Political 
Forces Dialogue Committee that the Yemeni Socialist Party [YSP] 
is floating a "new plan" that calls for the deployment of 
Egyptian troops between the northern Yemeni and southern Yemeni 
troops in the former border areas. 
  These sources added that 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih was informed 
of 
the new YSP plan by Egyptian Assistant Foreign Minister 
Ambassador Badr Hammam, who also met with YSP leaders in Aden, 
including 'Ali Salim al-Bid, secretary general of the YSP 
Central Committee and vice chairman of the Presidential Council. 
  Sources close to the General People's Congress said that it 
was Yemeni Prime Minister Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas who relayed 
the "new plan" to the Egyptian mediator. The sources added that 
the Presidential Council chairman expressed his strong 
dissatisfaction with the new plan, noting that it was only 
promoted by a minority within the YSP higher command, the 
majority of which cherishes unity. President Salih noted that 
this plan would return the country to the situation that 
prevailed before the merger unity of 22 May 1990. 
  In a separate development, and in a meeting with members of 
the Political Forces Dialogue Committee, the Yemeni president 
has denied that his country is importing banned weapons, saying: 
"Regardless of the differences in perspective we might have, we 
must resort to dialogue. We should not undermine national 
constants. Our unity must remain intact. It is better for us 
to come to the negotiating table to reach understanding and find 
solutions to our problems and hurdles before the onset of any 
armed conflicts or violence. This is because the failure to do 
so would result in bloodshed, devastation, and ruination 
throughout the homeland." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

