<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meets Mubarak, Comments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meets Mubarak, Comments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0604123394 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1150 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0604123394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 6 Apr (MENA)--President Husni Mubarak 
received Spanish Foreign Minister Javier Solana at the 
Presidential Palace at noon today. Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa 
and the Spanish ambassador in Cairo also attended the meeting. 
After the meeting, Musa said that the Spanish foreign minister 
conveyed a message to President Mubarak from Spanish prime 
minister Felipe Gonzalez dealing with bilateral ties, the peace 
process, Spain's position on it, and the situation in the 
Mediterranean, the Middle East, and Europe. He noted that the 
joint Egyptian-Spanish committee meetings concluded. He said: 
We studied bilateral ties in the cultural, economic, and trade 
fields. He expressed his belief that relations between Egypt 
and Spain are steadily growing. 
  Solana expressed his happiness to have met with President 
Mubarak. He noted that he discussed with President Mubarak 
developments in the peace process and the situation in the 
Mediterranean. He said that a conference on cooperation among 
Mediterranean countries will be held in Egypt on 1 June. He 
said that he conveyed an invitation to President Mubarak from 
the king of Spain to visit Madrid. He said: We hope that we 
will be able to set a date for the visit in the near future. He 
noted that his visit to Egypt was extremely successful, noting 
that he discussed cooperation in various fields. He said views 
were identical between Egypt and Spain regarding the Middle East 
and the Mediterranean region and solutions to numerous 
international problems that concern Spain and Egypt. 
  Asked if he had brought new ideas for the Middle East, 
Solana 
said: I hope that by 13 April an agreement will have been 
reached and that the peace process will proceed in a sound 
framework. He said that Spain is committed to helping further 
the peace process, noting the major role Egypt is playing to 
establish peace in the region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

