<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Bashir: U.S. Envoy `Did Not Touch on Anything New' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Bashir: U.S. Envoy `Did Not Touch on Anything New' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA0704212194 Omdurman Republic of Sudan Radio Network in 
Arabic 1300 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA0704212194 </F>
<F P=104>  Omdurman Republic of Sudan Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Lieutenant General 'Umar al-Bashir, the president 
of the Republic, has affirmed the cohesion of the internal front 
and its firm stand against all challenges facing the nation's 
march. During his meeting today with the leaders of information 
and press bodies at the general secretariat of the Council of 
Ministers, the president discussed the public's understanding of 
the revolution's programs and his perception of its achievements 
in various fields, particularly with regard to the security 
situation. 
  His excellency said recent attempts to cast doubt on the 
revolution's leadership by some people was due to personal 
reasons or to agents from foreign quarters. Lt. Gen. 'Umar 
al-Bashir said any conspirator who tried to hinder the Sudanese 
people would not be able to achieve his aims, pointing out that 
the revolution is proceeding despite all challenges. 
  The president of the Republic touched on the talks he held 
recently with U.S. envoy Madeleine Albright. He said President 
Clinton's envoy did not touch on anything new in the talks. He 
pointed out that she commented on the situation and the U.S. 
accusations against Sudan with regard to human rights, terrorism 
and relief. We submitted, during the talks, Sudan's stance 
towards the U.S. Administration, he said, adding that the 
contentious issue, in essence, was the issue of Islam. 
  Lt. Gen. al-Bashir described the meeting as the start of a 
serious dialogue between the two countries. He confirmed 
Sudan's desire to continue the dialogue, so that relations 
between Sudan and the United States would be based on a clear 
foundation. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

