<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Velayati, Yemeni Minister Note Bilateral Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Velayati, Yemeni Minister Note Bilateral Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704221094 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 1930 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0704221094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>

<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] During a meeting on Thursday 
evening between the foreign minister of Yemen and Mr. Velayati, 
our foreign minister, the two parties exchanged views on the 
historical ties between the two countries and regional and 
Islamic issues. They also expressed their interest in expanding 
and strengthening bilateral relations and stressed the need for 
the unity and solidarity of Islamic countries in order to 
neutralize the malicious plans of the enemies of Islam. 
  At the meeting, Mr. Velayati expressed our country's support 
for Yemeni unity and said that a solution for Yemen's problems 
and the existence of a strong and united Yemen are to the 
benefit of peace and stability in the region. He added: Those 
who want to create discord in the united ranks of Muslims have 
no interest in a united Yemen. 
  Our foreign minister, pointing out that alien powers cannot 
guarantee the region's security, stressed: The expansion of 
cooperation among Islamic countries is required for 
strengthening the world of Islam. The Islamic Republic of Iran 
believes that if such a cooperation had been prevalent in the 
Islamic world, the enemies of Islam would not have dared occupy 
Palestine, which is at the heart of the Islamic countries. 
  Mr. Muhammad Salim Basindwah, the Yemeni foreign minister, 
described the Islamic Republic of Iran as an important regional 
power and called for the expansion of bilateral relations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

