<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Musa Phones OAU Official on Rwanda, Comments on Yemen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Musa Phones OAU Official on Rwanda, Comments on Yemen </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0904160994 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1440 GMT 9 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0904160994 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 9 Apr (MENA)--Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa said 
today that he had telephoned OAU Secretary General Dr. Salim 
Ahmed Salim. Musa added that he had informed the OAU secretary 
general of the views of President Husni Mubarak, the OAU 
chairman, on the current tragedy in Rwanda and what the OAU 
ought to do to contain this tragedy. 
  The foreign minister said agreement was reached with the OAU 
secretary general to stay in touch while following the 
developments in Rwanda in order to put an end to the conflict. 
  He added that Salim Ahmed Salim told him that immediately 
after he returns from Tanzania the [OAU] body in charge of 
resolving African disputes will hold an urgent meeting at the 
ambassadorial level at OAU headquarters in Addis Ababa to follow 
up the situation in Rwanda. 
  On the situation in Yemen, Musa said that Information 
Minister Safwat al-Sharif left for Yemen today as the envoy of 
President Husni Mubarak, along with Rashid Bin-'Abdallah 
al-Na'imi, the United Arab Emirates foreign minister, as envoy 
of UAE President Shaykh Zayid Bin-Sultan, on a mission to follow 
up on the situation there and meet President 'Ali 'Abdallah 
Salih, his deputy 'Ali Salim al-Bid, and other leaders in an 
effort to take the necessary measures to preserve Yemeni 
stability and unity. 
  Musa added that he had held talks with the UAE foreign 
minister yesterday evening, that President Mubarak received the 
UAE minister today, and that all aspects of the issue and 
possible measures were discussed. 
  On his meeting today with the British Ambassador in Cairo, 
Christopher Long, Musa said several issues were discussed. He 
added that the ambassador conveyed a message from British 
Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd and an official invitation for 
him to visit Britain. The foreign minister said they also 
discussed the Middle East peace process and developments in the 
Libyan-Western crisis. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

