<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-069 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Tunisia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Issues Statement on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Issues Statement on Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1004224294 Tunis Tunisian Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
2100 GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1004224294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tunis Tunisian Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Foreign Ministry issued today a statement in 
which it said Tunisia is following with great concern the grave 
development in the situation in Bosnia due to the savage and 
escalating acts aiming at the unarmed civilian children of this 
country. 
  Tunisia, which had always stood by the causes of right, 
liberation, and justice, strongly condemns the policy of ethnic 
cleansing that blatantly contradict not only the right of the 
peoples to self-determination but also the most basic of human 
values and the most sacred of human rights -- namely the right 
to life. 
  Tunisia, which had blessed the accord concluded in 
Washington 
between the Croats and the Bosnian Muslims, demands an immediate 
end to this campaign and addresses an urgent appeal to the 
international community, particularly to the Security Council, 
to carry out a speedy and decisive action to halt this 
aggression against the innocents and to provide the 
circumstances that ensure security and peace in the region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

