<F P=101> Kuwait </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister on Resignation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister on Resignation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1004142694 Kuwait KUNA in Arabic 1246 GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1004142694 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuwait KUNA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Kuwait, 10 Apr -- Shaykh Sabah al-Ahmad, first 
deputy prime minister and foreign minister, said today that the 
aim of the ministers' decision to tender their resignations to 
His Highness Shaykh Sa'd al-'Abdallah Al-Salim al-Sabah, heir 
apparent and prime minister, was to give him the opportunity to 
re-form the government as he sees fit. 
  Shaykh Sabah al-Ahmad pointed out in an exclusive statement 
to KUNA that this step followed the address the heir apparent 
and prime minister delivered to the Kuwaiti people on Monday 
last. 
  He added that the ministers decided "to give Shaykh Sa'd the 
opportunity to choose whomever he wants to cooperate with, and 
this is his right." [passage omitted] 
  With reference to the National Assembly's call yesterday to 
maintain the presence of six deputies in the forthcoming 
ministerial formation, Shaykh Sabah al-Ahmad said "this is an 
issue for the prime minister." 
  Concerning his assessment of the experience of having six 
National Assembly members participating in the present 
government, Shaykh Sabah al-Ahmad said it was "not an experience 
inasmuch as the Constitution stipulates the presence of at least 
one member from the National Assembly in the ministerial 
formation." 
  He went on to say: "Therefore, the inclusion of the National 
Assembly was a necessity, as otherwise there would be no 
government from the constitutional point of view." [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

