<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. `Information' Reportedly Foils Assassination Plot </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. `Information' Reportedly Foils Assassination Plot </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0904083294 Amman AL-ASWAQ in Arabic 9 Apr 94 pp 1, 15 </F>
<F P=103> JN0904083294 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-ASWAQ </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by 'Abd-al-Rahman Husayn in Washington] </F>
  [Excerpt] The United States has conveyed urgent information 
to an Arab capital, thus foiling an assassination plot just a 
few days before its implementation. 
  According to the information, a plot targeted Yemeni 
President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih, along with certain military and 
civilian leaders. The plot was to be linked to the current 
differences between Yemeni leaders, whether this was revealed 
before or after its implementation, in a manner that would pave 
the way for wide- scale fighting--not just a possible clash 
between the north and the south--that would drown the whole of 
Yemen in waves of fighting. 
  The source of the information at the U.S. Department of 
State 
refused to give more details on the plot, but hinted that 
regional quarters were aware of the plan and supported the 
assassination plot, which was due to be carried out during the 
first half of this month. 
  The source declined to reveal whether the Yemeni capital, 
Sanaa, was informed of the details of the plot or if only the 
Arab capital in question was asked to withdraw its support for 
the assassination plot and its sponsorship of those 
masterminding it. 
  The source also refused to draw a link between the current 
military buildup in Yemen and the exchange of accusations 
between the two main parties on one hand, and the assassination 
plot that was exposed on the other. It seems that the Yemeni 
leadership in Sanaa was not directly informed about the plot. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

