<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-069 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Surani: Talks Not To Lead to `Honest' Implementation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Surani: Talks Not To Lead to `Honest' Implementation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1004111994 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 6 Apr 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> JN1004111994 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, AL-HAYAH -- PLO Executive Committee member 
Jamal al-Surani has said the Palestinian-Israeli Cairo talks on 
implementing the Gaza-Jericho agreement will not lead to an 
honest implementation of the Declaration of Principles [DOP]. 
  Al-Surani regretted that the Palestinian negotiator did not 
ask what had become of the original Palestine that was divided 
by Resolution 181. 
  In a statement to AL-HAYAH, he added that the Palestinian 
negotiator may get Gaza and the West Bank, a half or a quarter 
of it, and he may get nothing. This is because the United 
States and Israel have a special interpretation of Resolution 
242. They consider that Jerusalem is not an occupied city, that 
the occupied territories are not Palestinian but disputed 
territories, and they view settlements as legitimate. 
  He added: What is going on is not negotiations or peace 
because the crux of the Palestine question, which is the problem 
of refugees was excluded from the Madrid conference. 
  On the Syrian criticism that the Palestinian leadership 
separated the Palestinian-Israeli track from other tracks, 
al-Surani said: Syria has the right to say this, but it has no 
right to separate itself from the Palestine question. When 
Syrian Foreign minister Faruq al-Shar' criticized the 
Palestinian leadership he did so out of pain and bitterness, and 
his objective is the restoration of coordination and not to say 
goodbye to the Palestinians. 
  Al-Surani said: Regrettably, the Palestinian leadership is 
committing the mistake of acting unilaterally, and it should 
reconsider this situation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-12525 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes069yy_94019" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-069 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Reports on `Secret' Omani-Israeli Water Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Paper Reports on `Secret' Omani-Israeli Water Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1004080694 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 7 Apr 94 pp 1, 4 </F>
<F P=103> JN1004080694 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Husayn 'Abd-al-Ghani in Muscat] </F>
  [Text] AL-HAYAH has learned that water experts have held a 
meeting in Muscat. The meeting, which was kept secret by the 
Omani authorities, ended yesterday. 
  Diplomatic sources said that the participation of Israeli 
experts in an official meeting in an Arab country in the Gulf 
for the first time since the establishment of the Jewish state 
was behind the restricted reporting on the meeting. 
  The same sources added that experts from Oman, the United 
Kingdom, Jordan, the United Arab Emirates, Israel, and other 
countries attended the two-day meeting which was sponsored by 
the Omani Foreign Ministry. 
  The discussions dealt with the Omani experiment regarding 
the 
desalination of sea water and a study prepared by the Omanis to 
be presented to the meeting of the water committee affiliated 
with the Middle East peace conference which will be held in 
Muscat on 27 April. 
  The conferees reviewed the four five-year plans implemented 
in Oman in terms of building and developing water desalination 
stations, particularly the major water desalination plant in al- 
Ghabrah in the area of the capital, in which hundreds of 
millions of dollars are invested and which is the main source of 
drinking water for residents of the capital. 
  It appears that the need for further studies, researches, 
and 
working papers emerged during the meeting to crystallize Omani 
and Gulf concern for developing water desalination technology 
and reducing high economic costs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

