<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radio Sums Up Developments in Kashmir Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Radio Sums Up Developments in Kashmir Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1004161494 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 1530 
GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1004161494 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Jammu and Kashmir governor, General Krishna 
Rao, met the prime minister and the home minister in New Delhi. 
He is understood to have discussed with them measures to 
improve the situation in the state. 
  In Kashmir valley, militants shot dead a former MLA [member 
of legislative assembly], Mr. Ghulam Qadir Mir, last evening at 
his residence at village (Uran) in Pulwama District. An 
associate of late Sheikh Abdullah, Mir is the 11th former 
legislator to be killed by militants in the last four years. 
Meanwhile, two militants have been killed and 16 arrested 
during the last 24 hours. A large quantity of arms and 
ammunition was recovered from them. 
  The Indian ambassador to the United States, Mr. Sidhartha 
Shanker Ray, has said the accession of Jammu and Kashmir to 
India is legal, final, and irrevocable. He said there can be no 
compromise on the matter. Addressing the members of the Jammu 
Bar Association, Mr. Ray said the seizure of over 10,000 weapons 
supplied by Pakistan and the capture of foreign mercenaries is 
clear evidence of Islamabad's continuing support to the 
militants. He said the U.S. Administration is fully aware of 
Islamabad's direct involvement in terrorist activities. 

</TEXT>

