<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Financial Market, Assembly Ties Outlined </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Financial Market, Assembly Ties Outlined </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1104044494 Islamabad Radio Pakistan Network in Urdu 0200 
GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1104044494 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad Radio Pakistan Network </F>
<F P=105>  Urdu </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pakistan and Iran have agreed on a proposal to set 
up an Islamic financial common market [as heard]. An accord to 
this effect was reached in Islamabad yesterday during the 
meeting between Yusuf Raza Gilani, National Assembly speaker, 
and 'Ali Akbar Nateq, the head of the Iranian parliamentary 
delegation and the speaker of the Iranian Consultative Assembly. 
  The accords provide for the establishment of a separate 
organization comprising the Muslim member nations of the 
Interparliamentary Union and Economic Cooperation Organization 
and a conference for female parliament members from Muslim 
countries. At the meeting, the Iranian parliament speaker 
condemned the hegemonic trends appearing in international 
relations. 
  Nateq also called on President Farooq Ahmad Khan Leghari. 

</TEXT>

