<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres: No Talks on Permanent Status of Territories </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Peres: No Talks on Permanent Status of Territories </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0904192494 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 9 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0904192494 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 9 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=105> Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report on interview with Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres and </F>
Environment Minister Yosi Sarid by correspondent Hezi Makhlev on 
9 April; place not given--recorded] 
  [Text] [Makhlev] This evening, the foreign minister 
commented on PLO official Yasir 'Abd-Rabbuh's demand to 
immediately start negotiations over the permanent status of the 
territories instead of holding talks over autonomy in the Gaza 
Strip and Jericho. 
  [Peres] I do not accept his view. There is an agreement that 
must be implemented. This is what we will do. Anyone 
attempting to achieve permanent peace today might only create a 
permanent dispute by bringing up unresolvable issues. 
  [Makhlev] Sir, PLO circles are demanding immediate 
negotiations over the permanent status in the territories 
instead of holding talks on autonomy in the Gaza Strip and 
Jericho. 
  [Peres] I do not know what you mean by circles. We are 
conducting negotiations with the PLO leadership and with Mr. 
'Arafat. We are holding talks with him and have not heard any 
such demands at the negotiating table. 
  [Makhlev] Do you plan to meet Mr. 'Arafat after Independence 
Day in order to clarify these issues? 
  [Peres] If necessary, I will meet with him, but nothing has 
been scheduled yet. 
  [Makhlev] Meretz is demanding to limit the closure and to be 
generous in issuing work permits. What is your reaction to this? 
  [Peres] My response is that the place to discuss this issue 
is within the framework of the cabinet. 
  [Makhlev] Environment Minister Yosi Sarid, some of your 
colleagues in Meretz are requesting to ease the closure and to 
be more generous in issuing work permits to laborers from the 
territories. 
  [Sarid] First of all, I would like to say that I support the 
closure; however, I do not think that the government should tie 
its hands now by making definitive decisions on the duration of 
the closure. We know that closures have their limitations which 
we have to take into account. There are humanitarian needs of 
the first degree, and there is no need to make far-reaching 
decisions only to later backtrack from them. Therefore, the 
government should tomorrow evaluate the closure, which I 
support, and examine its duration and limitations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

